1 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES - FLOOR VERSION
2 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
3 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
4 ENGROSSED SENATE
CONCURRENT
5 RESOLUTION NO. 22 By: Nice of the Senate
6 and
7 Hefner of the House
8
9 A Concurrent Resolution recognizing the impact of
light pollution on bird mortality; and encouraging
10 Oklahoma businesses, state agencies, organizations,
and residents to turn off any exterior lighting
11 during the high migration intensity months of April,
May, September and October.
12
13
14 WHEREAS, the State of Oklahoma and the Oklahoma Animal Coalition
15 aim to provide birds safe passage during migration periods by
16 reducing light pollution, as well as building and glass collisions,
17 through the Lights Out Oklahoma campaign; and
18 WHEREAS, birds help with the control of pests, carrion
19 regulation, pollination, and seed dispersal while adding beauty and
20 connecting people to nature and the outdoors; and
21 WHEREAS, birdwatching is an economic driver in the State of
22 Oklahoma and is a fun, relaxing, multigenerational, educational and
23 wellness activity for all; and
24
SCR22 HFLR
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
Page 1

1 WHEREAS, a wide diversity of birds in Oklahoma indicates a
2 healthy environment; and
3 WHEREAS, Oklahoma is part of the central flyway through which
4 approximately 400 different species of birds migrate during the
5 spring and fall; and
6 WHEREAS, the Oklahoma state bird, the scissor-tailed flycatcher,
7 is one of the many species of birds that migrate to our state to
8 nest and rear their young; and
9 WHEREAS, most birds migrate at night, navigate by using the
10 stars and moon, and can become disoriented by bright artificial
11 light and sky glow, resulting in exhaustion and deadly collisions
12 with buildings, glass, power lines, and vehicles; and
13 WHEREAS, collisions with buildings is one of the top causes of
14 mortality of birds in the United States; and
15 WHEREAS, the Lights Out Oklahoma program strategy is aimed to
16 persuade building owners and managers and homeowners to turn off
17 exterior lighting on all buildings at night during the high
18 migration intensity months of April, May, September and October; and
19 WHEREAS, these measures save energy and money and protect birds
20 migrating to nesting grounds in the spring and wintering grounds in
21 the fall; and
22 WHEREAS, Oklahoma joins the international community and states
23 including Texas, Colorado, Kansas, Missouri and Florida in
24 sponsoring Lights Out projects to protect birds during migration.
SCR22 HFLR
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
Page 2

1 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE 2ND SESSION
2 OF THE 60TH OKLAHOMA LEGISLATURE, THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
3 CONCURRING THEREIN:
4 THAT the Oklahoma State Legislature supports reducing bird
5 mortality in the areas and encourages Oklahoma businesses, state
6 agencies, organizations, and residents to turn off any exterior
7 lighting during the high migration intensity months of April, May,
8 September and October.
9
10 DIRECT TO CALENDAR.
